        "Tafseer": "1. Analysis of Words and Explanation of Verses\n\nThose who disbelieve and avert [people] from the way of Allah - He will waste their deeds. (1)\n\nWarning to the Disbelievers of the Quraysh\n\nThe previous Surah, Al-Ahqaf, ended with a threat and warning to the disbelievers. This Surah begins with that very same theme without any introduction, as if it is the practical manifestation of that threat. It states: those who disbelieved and turned people away from the path of Allah, Allah made all their efforts go to waste. This points, obviously, to the polytheists of Makkah. Its details will follow under verse 25 of Surah Al-Fath. 'Deeds' ('a'malahum) refers to those activities which they dedicated to turn Allah's servants away from the path of faith and righteous deeds. 'Idhlal' (wasting) is used here in the same sense in which 'tadhlil' is used in Surah Al-Feel: 'Did He not make their plan into misguidance [i.e., waste]?' (Al-Feel: 2)—meaning: 'Did Allah not destroy all their planning?' This theme will also follow below in verses 4, 32, and 33 of this Surah.\n\nIt should be kept in mind here: although this warning relates to the future, as the Quraysh were still dominant over Makkah at the time of this Surah's sending down, yet the statement has occurred in the past tense. The reason is what we have been explaining in various places: what has been decisively resolved by Allah and whose occurrence is certain is as if it has already occurred, because no one has the power to alter His decisions. To express this certainty, Allah Almighty's promises and warnings in the Qur'an have also occurred in the past tense. This style is well-known in every language, and its benefits are entirely clear."
