    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 2,
        "Tafseer": "\"And those who believe and do righteous deeds and believe in what has been sent down upon Muhammad - and it is the truth from their Lord - He will remove from them their misdeeds and amend their condition.\" (2)\n\nGlad Tidings for the Believers\n\nWhile the preceding verse contained a severe warning to the disbelievers, this verse contains glad tidings of success in both this world and the Hereafter for the believers, expressed in the same style of discourse. It states: those who believed, performed righteous deeds, and believed in what was sent down upon Muhammad, Allah Almighty removed their lapses from them and amended all their conditions.\n\nJust as the warning to the disbelievers was expressed in the past tense to show its certainty, the glad tidings for the believers is also expressed in the past tense.\n\nThe True Religion is Only That Which Was Sent Down upon the Prophet (pbuh)\n\nIn this verse, the words 'and believe in what has been sent down upon Muhammad - and it is the truth from their Lord' are worthy of attention. It does not state merely: 'those who believed and did righteous deeds will face this dealing from Allah'; but is also accompanied by the clarification: 'and believed in what has been sent down upon Muhammad,' and further, 'and it is the truth from their Lord.' This clarification was required because during that period, a group of people had arisen who talked of compromise between disbelief and Islam. Their perspective was: the Muslims' persistence on their separate identity is not correct, but some room must be accepted for others. Among the People of the Book, a group also claimed: 'We are also believers, so what difference does it make if we do not believe in Muhammad (pbuh).' The Qur'an refuted such baseless tendencies in the previous Surahs. Here also, this clarification has struck at this tendency—showing that the sole path of faith and guidance is that to which Muhammad (pbuh) is inviting, and there is no other path besides it.\n\n'and amend their condition' (wa-aslaha balahum)—'Bal' is a comprehensive word, encompassing both apparent and hidden states; therefore, its meaning is: Allah Almighty will amend all their states of the apparent and hidden, and of this world and the Hereafter."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 3,
        "Tafseer": "\"That is because those who disbelieve follow falsehood, and those who believe follow the truth from their Lord. Thus does Allah present to the people their parables.\" (3)\n\nTrue Power is Within the Truth\n\nThis describes the cause of why the efforts of the disbelievers will go to waste, and why the believers will succeed in their efforts. It states: this is because the disbelievers followed the falsehood taught by Satan, and the believers followed the truth which came from their Lord. Falsehood has no place in human nature and reason. Its example is like a wild bush which grows in the farmer's land due to his negligence. If it is not uprooted, it takes root, and if it is uprooted, it is entirely weak. Thus, now when the people of truth have stood up to fight with this falsehood, its perishing is certain: 'The truth has come, and falsehood has vanished. Indeed, falsehood is ever bound to vanish.' (Al-Isra': 81).\n\nOn the contrary, the believers followed the truth which came from their Lord. Within the nature of truth lies stability and robustness. This is because the Creator of this universe is Truth, and He has created this world in truth. Its actual character is not to nurture falsehood, but to nurture truth.\n\nNow, when the truth has come, it will necessarily reject the falsehood which had overcome it. This shows that the primary power is within the truth, not in resources. If the conflict is between falsehood and falsehood, the decision is indeed in the hands of resources; but if the conflict is between truth and falsehood, the primary decision-making importance belongs to the truth, and the status of resources becomes secondary.\n\n'Thus does Allah present to the people their parables'—since the end of both groups was still a prophecy at this stage, having not yet taken the form of a real event, it was expressed as presenting a parable. 'The people' (Al-Nas) refers to the believers and disbelievers mentioned above. The meaning is: Allah Almighty has presented this parable of the end of both groups, and its reality will soon stand manifest before everyone."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 4,
        "Tafseer": "\"So when you meet those who disbelieve [in battle], strike [their] necks until, when you have inflicted slaughter upon them, then secure their bonds, and either [confer] favor afterwards or ransom until the war lays down its burdens. That [is the command]. And if Allah had willed, He could have taken retribution from them [Himself], but [He ordered war] in order to test some of you with others. And those who are killed in the cause of Allah - never will He waste their deeds.\" (4)\n\nThe Disbelievers Lack a Backbone\n\nThis encourages the Muslims—showing that since the disbelievers are deprived of the support of the truth, they lack a backbone; so when you meet them in battle, strike their necks without hesitation. Allah has made them a prey for you and a fresh morsel for your swords. This is expressed in Surah Al-Anfal: 'so strike [them] upon the necks and strike from them every fingertip.' (12).\n\n'until, when you have inflicted slaughter upon them, then secure their bonds'—'ithkhan' means to inflict heavy slaughter, and 'wathaq' means bonds. The meaning is: when you have broken their strength through heavy slaughter, secure those who survive in bonds. They will not be able to do anything against you.\n\n'and either [confer] favor afterwards or ransom until the war lays down its burdens'—meaning: after this, if they are to be released, let them be released only in two ways: either out of favor (without ransom) or in exchange for ransom, and your dealing with them must remain of this kind until the passion for war is completely cooled within them and they surrender before you. In another place, He stated: 'And fight them until there is no fitnah and [until] the religion, all of it, is for Allah.' (Al-Anfal: 39).\n\nThe Specific Nature of Dealing with the Children of Ismail\n\nIt should be clear: regarding the polytheists of the Children of Ismail, since Allah Almighty fully established proof against them by sending a messenger from among themselves, unlike other non-Muslims, there was no allowance for them to remain as protected citizens (Dhimmi) or allies in the Islamic state, nor could they be made slaves. For them, only two paths remained: Islam or the sword. The detailed explanation of this has passed in the commentary of Surah At-Tawbah. A Muslim prisoner could be released in exchange for their prisoner or for ransom, or their prisoner could be released out of favor, and if any of them requested refuge to reflect on his attitude, he could be given refuge, but as a community, the state of war with them was to remain until the land of Haram was completely purified of every trace of shirk. The differences among the jurists on this issue are highly confusing. The explanation of this has passed in the commentary of Surah At-Tawbah. Here, the matter discussed is of the polytheists of the Children of Ismail; other non-Muslims are not discussed.\n\nImam Abu Hanifah's view—that the allowance of favor and ransom regarding the polytheists was abrogated, and they can only be killed or made slaves—is correct to the extent that this allowance regarding the Arab polytheists was temporary and ended after the Conquest of Makkah; but his view that they can be made slaves is, in our view, incorrect. The Arab polytheists could neither be made slaves, nor Dhimmis, nor allies.\n\nAccording to Imam Shafi'i, the leader has the choice, keeping in view the interest of Islam and the Muslims, to deal with such prisoners in whichever of the four ways he considers suitable: he can have them killed, make them slaves, release them for ransom, or release them out of favor. In our view, this general rule of Imam Shafi'i is correct regarding general non-Muslim prisoners, but is not correct regarding the Arab polytheists. They could neither be made Dhimmis nor slaves. There is no room to go into details here. Those who seek details should read the chapter 'The Rights of Non-Muslims in the Islamic State' in our book *Islamic State*.\n\n'That [is the command]. And if Allah had willed, He could have taken retribution from them [Himself], but [He ordered war] in order to test some of you with others'—'That' (Dhalika) stands in place of a sentence, and several examples of this have passed. Its clear meaning is: this is the task which is for you to do, or this is the task for which you must gird up your loins. This style of omission has the benefit of containing details within itself, and also produces force in the sentence.\n\nThe Wisdom of Jihad\n\n'And if Allah had willed...'—meaning: Allah's commanding you to fight is not because He is in need of you or anyone else to deal with them. If He had willed, He could have destroyed them by sending some earthly or heavenly calamity. Many nations passed before whom He destroyed in the blink of an eye. In the same way, He could have destroyed these, but He commanded you to fight so that both you and they are tested. The passion and devotion they have for their falsehood stands manifest, as does the devotion and loyalty you have for your truth, and it also becomes clear who among you is sincere and loyal, and who is a hypocrite who has entered your ranks only for his own interests.\n\nA Sunnah of Allah\n\nKeep in view also this Sunnah of Allah: regarding the messengers, His dealing has been: if the number of those who believed in the messenger was very small, the messenger and his companions were commanded to migrate, and Allah destroyed all his deniers by some earthly or heavenly calamity; and if the number of his companions was significant, they were commanded to perform Jihad, and Allah took retribution from their enemies through their hands. This was the dealing with the Prophet (pbuh). Before you, prophets and messengers had to perform Jihad. Against Pharaoh, He helped Hazrat Musa (peace be upon him) and the Children of Israel through the storm of the sea. Then, after crossing the sea, they had to fight various small and large battles themselves, in which the Children of Israel were tested. They failed in most tests, for which they were punished.\n\nRefuting a Assumption of the Hypocrites\n\n'And those who are killed in the cause of Allah - never will He waste their deeds'—meaning those who are martyred in this Jihad should rest assured: Allah Almighty will not let their efforts go to waste, but will fully reward them for this sacrifice. The words 'never will He waste their deeds' (falay-yudilla 'amalahum) are said keeping in view the assumption of the hypocrites, whose mention is coming. Since they did not believe in the Hereafter, they considered every sacrifice a loss whose benefit was not received immediately. These words strike at their assumption. The statement regarding those who are martyred—showing that do not consider them dead, but they are alive—is also to refute such people.\n\nIn 'And those who are killed' (Walladhina qutiloo), the past tense is used instead of the future so that this glad tidings also encompasses those who were martyred in the path of truth before."
