        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 5,
        "Tafseer": "\"He will guide them and amend their condition And admit them to Paradise, which He has made known to them.\" (5-6)\n\nWhat was stated in the preceding verse with 'never will He waste their deeds' in a negative style is stated here in a positive style to make the matter fully clear and emphasized. It states: Allah Almighty will guide them and amend all their conditions. By guiding them, the guidance to the final destination is meant—meaning Allah Almighty will deliver them to their final destination, Paradise.\n\nThe word 'guidance' (hidayah) is used in various places in the Qur'an in this sense. Its parallels have passed and will come. Within 'amend their condition' (wa-yuslihu balahum) is summarized all that detail of the believers' honor and success which has been described in the Qur'an, rather within it is also a subtle allusion to those honors which have been mentioned with the words: 'And no soul knows what has been hidden for them of comfort for eyes' (As-Sajdah: 17).\n\nThe Promise of Paradise is No Obscure Promise\n\n'And admit them to Paradise, which He has made known to them'—regarding this Paradise, He stated: 'He has made it known to them' ('arrafa-ha lahum). This clarification was required so that no one remains in the misconception: this promise of Paradise is an obscure promise, without any knowledge of its details! If some contract is obscure, its details unclear, the weak party remains in fear as to what interpretation would be made of it. To protect His servants from such fears regarding the promise of Paradise, He has informed them of all its details in the Qur'an, and has also pointed to those matters which are beyond description, so that the servants are fully assured: the thing for which they have handed over their lives to their Lord is no obscure thing, but all its details are settled, and Allah Almighty has taken the responsibility not only to fulfill them, but has also promised further increases. While this description of Paradise is mentioned throughout the Qur'an, its details are specifically mentioned in this Surah as well. See verse 15. It should be clear that 'He has made it known to them' ('arrafa-ha lahum) is not an adjective qualifying 'Paradise'. If it had been so, 'Paradise' would have been indefinite. Rather, they hold the status of an independent sentence, and from its being an independent sentence is produced that meaning to which we have pointed."
