    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 7,
        "Tafseer": "\"O you who have believed, if you support Allah, He will support you and plant firmly your feet. And those who disbelieve - for them is misery, and He will waste their deeds. That is because they disliked what Allah revealed, so He rendered worthless their deeds.\" (7-9)\n\nWhen Does Divine Help Appear\n\nThis encourages the Muslims—showing: your duty is to stand up to support Allah and His religion. If you stand up with resolve, your Lord will manage the subsequent work. He will help you and plant your feet firmly in such a way that no one can shake them. The meaning is: Allah Almighty desires of His servants only that they take the first step in His path. If they take this step, His manifestations will appear. His help does not descend upon those who sit in their houses waiting for it; but it descends upon those who place themselves in the field and then wait for His help.\n\n'And those who disbelieve - for them is misery'—this describes the fate of the disbelievers: for them is the curse of God, and He will make all their deeds go to waste. The respite they received was for trial and the establishment of proof; now, if you stand up to deal with them, you will see that all their efforts will perish. 'Ta'san lahum' (misery/destruction for them) is a phrase of curse, and its usage in this sense is well-known.\n\nThe Cause of the Disbelievers' Ruin\n\n'That is because they disliked what Allah revealed, so He rendered worthless their deeds'—this describes the cause of why they have become so weak and deserving of the curse of God: this was because they disliked what Allah Almighty sent down for their guidance, and remained clung to their innovations and deviations. As a retribution, Allah made those deeds of theirs go to waste which they performed considering them works of religion. This points to those deeds which were apparently of virtue, but due to their shirk, went to waste. Some of these deeds have been mentioned in Surah At-Tawbah—such as managing the Haram and serving the pilgrims. The polytheists were proud of these services of theirs. But these worldly services proved to be entirely without weight in the scale of Allah. With Allah Almighty, only those deeds are acceptable which are performed in accordance with His conditions; He is not in need of anyone's virtue, such that He would be indebted to accept whatever way anyone performed a virtue."
