    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 14,
        "Tafseer": "\"Then is he who is on a clear proof from his Lord like him to whom the evil of his work has been made attractive and they follow their desires?\" (14)\n\nThe Testimony of Reason and Nature for the Believers' Good End\n\nIn the preceding verse, their worldly end was pointed to, supported by historical proof. This points to their اخروی end, and presents human reason and nature as witnesses. It asks: is he who is on a clear proof from his Lord, walking in this light, like the one in whose eyes his evil deed has been made attractive and who is following his desires? The meaning is: this can never be. This is contrary to reason and nature. If this were so, it would mean that this world is a place of lawlessness, and its Creator is a player!\n\nThe analysis of 'Bayyinah' has passed in Surah Yunus. Allah Almighty has imbued a decisive proof within human nature, and supported it further with the light of His revelation. These two combine to make the inner state of man light upon light, as has been explained in Surah An-Nur, whose brightness is necessarily manifest in his apparent life. On the contrary, the one who extinguishes the light of his nature remains deprived of the light of revelation, the result of which is that his apparent and hidden states are both dark. The meaning is: those whose apparent and hidden states are so different, how can they be equal in their end!\n\nIf you reflect, in the mention of the believers, only their inner state is highlighted, without mentioning their apparent; and in the mention of the disbelievers, their apparent is referred to, while ignoring their inner state. In the light of the principle of contrast, fill this gap, and then the eloquence of this verse will stand manifest.\n\nIn the verse, the pronouns and verbs for 'man' (who/whoever) are used in both singular and plural, because this is shared among singular, plural, masculine, and feminine."
