    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 15,
        "Tafseer": "\"Is the description of Paradise, which the righteous are promised, wherein are rivers of water unaltered, rivers of milk the taste of which never changes, rivers of wine delicious to those who drink, and rivers of purified honey, in which they will have from all [kinds of] fruits and forgiveness from their Lord, like [the state of] those who abide eternally in the Fire and are given to drink scalding water so it severs their intestines?\" (15)\n\nThe Parable of Paradise\n\nThat is, when the equal end of both groups is contrary to reason and nature, it is necessary that those who spent their lives in accordance with their upright nature and the light of Allah's guidance are rewarded by Him with His mercy, and those who followed their desires face the retribution for their deviation. Consequently, the end of both will be entirely different. Allah has promised the pious of Paradise, whose parable is: within it will be rivers of un-altered water, springs of un-changed milk, rivers of wine which will be pure pleasure for the drinkers without any evil, and rivers of clear honey; further, they will have all kinds of fruits, and permanent glad tidings of forgiveness from their Lord. On the contrary, the other group will abide eternally in Hell, and their first hospitality will be with boiling water which will sever their intestines.\n\nA Look at the Purity of the Blessings\n\nReflect on this: the purity of the blessings of Paradise is specifically highlighted. The reason is: the source of all blessings is Paradise, but when they are received in this world, they pass through so many stages and mediums that their true nature is changed, and their form is distorted. Take water: it passes through atmosphere, clouds, winds, rivers, streams, and earth; obviously, it is affected by every stage, because of which its nature which is in its source, Paradise, is changed.\n\nSimilarly, take milk: in this world, it passes through 'excrement and blood' (An-Nahl: 66) to reach us. Reflect: how can the blessing of Paradise which passes through this way remain on its actual characteristics. For this reason, the difference between the milk and honey of Paradise and of this world is like the difference between the sky and the earth. From these blessings of the world, you can form a general idea of those blessings, and Allah Almighty gave these temporary blessings to us specifically so that we could imagine those real blessings; but the relation is after all of reality and metaphor. This relation must not be ignored.\n\nPure Blessings are Specific to Those of Upright Nature\n\nIf you reflect on the connection of this verse with verse 14, another reality stands manifest: Allah Almighty has specified these blessings in their actual form for those of His servants who protect their nature, which Allah has described as: 'the fitrah of Allah upon which He has created people' (Ar-Rum: 30), from every trace of corruption, and return to their Lord with a sound heart. As for those who distort their nature to become slaves of their desires, and pollute their sound heart, they have no share in these blessings. They enjoyed whatever they had to enjoy in this world. In the Hereafter, for them is that punishment which is the logical consequence of distorting their nature.\n\nHaving understood the meaning, have a look at the words and sentences:\n\n'Asin' (unaltered) is used as an adjective for that water whose color and taste have changed. It should be kept in mind: the treatment for the physical diseases produced by bad water is with no physician.\n\nRegarding milk: 'the taste of which never changes' (lam yataghayyar ta'muhu). This refers to that change in taste which is manifest from its corruption. Milk is a natural food; because of this, its corruption is a major corruption.\n\nWith 'wine' (khamr), the attribute 'delicious' (ladhdhah) contains the meaning of exaggeration, like 'Zaydun adlun'. That is: it will be pure pleasure, and the drinkers will experience no bitterness, hangover, or bad effects from it, nor will it incite bammasti and sin.\n\nWith 'honey' (asal), the attribute 'purified' (musaffa) shows the reality: the honey available in this world is received through the medium of bees, which cannot be free from their impurity. The honey of Paradise will emerge from its source. No one will be able to criticize it.\n\n'and forgiveness from their Lord' is mentioned at the end as the greatest blessing of Paradise, because the forgiveness and pleasure of God is what guarantees all these blessings, and from it open the paths of further ranks.\n\nBefore 'like [the state of] those who abide eternally in the Fire' (kaman huwa khalidun fin-nar), the words: 'is he who has the like of this Paradise' or a similar expression is omitted due to contextual clarity. Omission in interrogative and conditional sentences is well-known. Precedents have passed.\n\nDrinking boiling water is mentioned as the first hospitality (nuzul) of the people of Hell."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 16,
        "Tafseer": "\"And among them are those who listen to you, until when they depart from you, they say to those who were given knowledge, 'What did he say just now?' Those are the ones upon whose hearts Allah has set a seal, and they follow their desires.\" (16)\n\nPointing to a Group of the Hypocrites\n\nThis warned the Prophet (pbuh) of those who were apparently with the Muslims, but all their sympathies were with the opponents of Islam. Warning of them was required because in the preceding verses, the Muslims were instructed to prepare for a major mission, which could be harmed most by such people. It states: among them is a group who lend their ears to listen to your words, but hear and understand nothing. Their state is: when they leave your gathering, they ask the other people of knowledge: 'Brother, what did he say just now?'\n\nThe referent of the pronoun in 'among them' (minhum) is that group which was mentioned with 'disliked what Allah revealed' above. That is: one group does not approach you at all due to their aversion, and among them is also a group who come to you but not to hear and understand, but completely as hypocrites.\n\nBy asking 'What did he say just now?', one impression they wanted to give was: 'As far as listening is concerned, we also listened and are ready to act upon it with heart and soul, but we have not understood what he wants to command.' In this way, they tried to cover up their hypocrisy.\n\nThe second impression they wanted to give was: 'These words are not such as to say \"we believe and obey\" without any thought; but they need to be reflected upon and understood.' In this way, by their phrase, they tried to discourage those Muslims who said 'we believe and obey' to every word of the Prophet (pbuh)—implying: 'You say so merely out of simplicity, we listen with great attention but do not understand.' It should be clear: this is a highly effective way to make even the best of statements doubtful. With this objective, these hypocrites also did this: when any Surah was revealed and the Prophet (pbuh) recited it, on leaving the gathering, they asked sarcastically: 'Brother, whose faith has been increased by this Surah!' In Surah At-Tawbah, their mischief is mentioned as:\n\n'And whenever a surah is revealed, there are among them [i.e., the hypocrites] those who say, \"Which of you has this increased in faith?\" As for those who believed, it has increased them in faith, and they rejoice. But as for those in whose hearts is disease, it only adds filth to their filth, and they die while they are disbelievers.' (124-125).\n\n'Those are the ones upon whom hearts Allah has set a seal, and they follow their desires'—this points to verse 14 above: 'like him to whom the evil of his work has been made attractive and they follow their desires'—showing that their bad deeds have been made attractive in their eyes and they are following their desires; because of this, they will face the end destined for such people. Such people deprive themselves of the light of nature; because of this, they remain deprived of the light of revelation, and due to their bad deeds, their hearts are sealed."
