        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 18,
        "Tafseer": "\"Then do they await except the Hour that it should come to them unexpectedly? But already there have come its indications. Then how, when it has come to them, will they have their reminder?\" (18)\n\nFor Those Who Await the Punishment, Is Only Punishment\n\nThat is, if the Prophet's words are not being understood by them, it means they are waiting only for the decisive Hour to come upon them unexpectedly. 'Al-Sa'ah' (the Hour) can refer to the Resurrection, and also to that decisive punishment which necessarily comes upon a nation for denying the messenger. Allah's messengers warned their nations of both of these punishments, and the relation between the two is of the introduction and the completion. The meaning is: Allah showed His favor to these people by sending His messenger and His Book to warn them, so that when that Hour comes, they cannot say that no warner came to them; but their state is: they are trying to remain ignorant. If they are remaining ignorant, let them; Allah sends His messenger for the final establishment of proof. If they do not wake up even by His reminding, the final thing is the punishment and the Resurrection. Now they will face it, and since they do not value the warnings, it means they want it unexpectedly.\n\nThe Indications of the Punishment\n\n'But already there have come its indications'—meaning if they await the Hour, they should know that its indications have become prominent. This points to that Sunnah of Allah which has been described—showing that Allah Almighty does not send His decisive punishment upon any nation until He sends His messenger to their central city. This has occurred, and Allah is watching what the nation does with the messenger. Until now, what the nation has done deserves punishment, but Allah Almighty is granting further respite so that whoever wishes to regain their senses may do so.\n\nIf people do not regain their senses, the law of God will be implemented. Allah Almighty will separate His good servants, and destroy those who persist on rebellion. The traces of this end are becoming prominent in the horizons and ourselves, and will become more prominent. To the extent that the judgment between the believers and the disbelievers will be made by Allah Almighty in this world as well, and this judgment will be the introduction to the major judgment of the Hereafter. After the final messenger's advent, this is the subsequent stage. Thus, in some Hadiths, the Prophet (pbuh) also pointed to this. Raising two of his fingers, you stated: 'Just as there is no distance between these two, there is no distance between my advent and the Resurrection.'\n\n'Then how, when it has come to them, will they have their reminder?'—the referent of the subject is 'Al-Sa'ah' (the Hour) mentioned above. The meaning is: if they are waiting for the Hour to believe, then whether it appears in the form of the decisive punishment or the Resurrection, where will remain any opportunity for them to receive warning! The opportunity to benefit from this reminding is only as long as it is hidden. Once it is manifest, no one's faith will hold any value."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 19,
        "Tafseer": "\"So know, [O Muhammad], that there is no deity except Allah and ask forgiveness for your sin and for the believing men and believing women. And Allah knows your movement and your resting place.\" (19)\n\nThis points to the reality: the Hour has drawn near, so know well that there is no deity besides Allah. Those who are carefree relying on their assumed partners will know well at that time that against God, no one is their helper.\n\nInstruction of Preparation to Protect from the Punishment\n\n'and ask forgiveness for your sin and for the believing men and believing women'—this instructed the Prophet (pbuh) to prepare to remain safe from the afflictions of that time: 'leave those who are careless to their state, and continuously ask forgiveness of your Lord for your lapses and for the lapses of the believing men and believing women.'\n\nThis addresses the Prophet (pbuh) as the representative and intercessor of the Ummah. Allah's messenger carries the burden of all his companions, men and women, and continuously asks forgiveness for himself and for them. He was instructed to perform this with greater care so that when the Hour appears, the believers remain safe from its afflictions.\n\nHere, the attribution of 'sin' (dhanb) to the Prophet (pbuh) is, as we pointed out, as the representative of the Ummah, not as the personally responsible one. Moreover, the lapses committed by the Prophets (peace be upon them) are not of the nature of following desires, but only: sometimes they exceed the specified limits in following the truth. This has been explained. This kind of excess is in itself no sin, but since the honorable Prophets (peace be upon them) are the touchstone of truth, Allah Almighty takes them to account and corrects them.\n\nGuaranty of Protection to the Prophet (pbuh) and the Muslims\n\n'And Allah knows your movement and your resting place'—'mutaqallab' can be a verbal noun and also an adverb. Keeping in view the word 'mathwa' (resting place), we have taken it in the sense of an adverb—meaning the place of going and coming.\n\nThis guaranteed protection to the Prophet (pbuh) and the Muslims—showing that if you continuously ask forgiveness of your Lord, wherever you are, Allah Almighty will protect you. He knows well your movements and your resting places. There is no fear that you will fall under the punishment."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 20,
        "Tafseer": "\"And those who believe say, 'Why has a surah not been sent down?' But when a precise surah is sent down and fighting is mentioned therein, you see those in whose hearts is disease [i.e., hypocrisy] looking at you with a look of one overcoming by death. So more appropriate for them [would have been]\" (20)\n\nThe Hypocrites' Aversion to Jihad\n\nThis points to that attitude of the hypocrites which they adopted after hearing the explicit command of Jihad (verse 4). It states: previously, to establish the show of their faith, they demanded that no clear command of Jihad was sent down; but when a precise Surah is sent down and in highly clear terms Jihad is mentioned, those in whose hearts is the disease of hypocrisy look at you with the look of one on whom the agony of death has overcome.\n\nBefore 'And those who believe say' (Wa-yaqoolu), an auxiliary verb is omitted according to the rules of Arabic—meaning: 'and those who claim to believe used to say'.\n\n'Those who believe' (Alladhina amanoo) is used in the sense of 'those who claim to believe', and using the verb to mean its claim is well-known in Arabic. For example: 'O you who have believed, believe in Allah and His Messenger...' (An-Nisa': 136).\n\nAfter 'Why has a surah not been sent down?' (Lawla nuzzilat surah), the words 'regarding Jihad' or 'regarding fighting' are omitted. It is a well-known style of the Qur'an: if the detail of something is coming below, first its brief mention is made. Below in verse 36 of this Surah, its parallel is coming. In quoting people's questions, this same method is adopted. We have explained this under 'They ask you concerning the new moons' (Al-Baqarah: 189). The meaning is: previously they demanded with great zeal: 'Why is the command of Jihad not sent down in explicit words?'; but now when it has been sent down, they are hiding.\n\n'precise surah' (suratun muhkamah)—'muhkamah' (precise/decisive) shows its certainty and its being free of need of interpretation. That is: it contains no o-ambiguity to stand in need of interpretation, nor is it of the category of allegorical verses whose interpretation is known only to Allah Almighty.\n\n'you see those in whose hearts is disease'—'disease' (maradh) refers to hypocrisy and also to that malice and envy which these hypocrites harbored against Islam and the Prophet (pbuh). Below in verses 29 and 37 of this Surah, its explanation is coming. Its analysis has passed in Surah Al-Baqarah.\n\nThis depiction of the hypocrites has also passed in Surah An-Nisa':\n\n'Have you not seen those who were told, \"Restrain your hands and establish prayer and give zakah\"? But when fighting was ordained for them, at once a party of them feared men as they fear Allah or with [even] greater fear.' (An-Nisa': 77).\n\nThat is: as long as the command of Jihad was not sent down, they made tall claims of their loyalty to show their zeal; but when it was sent down, they fear men more than they fear Allah, and are hiding.\n\n'So more appropriate for them' (fa'awla lahum) is a word of curse and expression of aversion. Its meaning is like 'waylun lahum'. The meaning is: when, along with the claim of faith, they have nurtured hypocrisy and cowardice within themselves, let them be cursed!"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 21,
        "Tafseer": "\"[Obedience] and appropriate speech. And when the matter [of fighting] was determined, if they had been true to Allah, it would have been better for them.\" (21)\n\nThe Correct Requirement of Faith\n\nThat is, the correct way for them was: they accepted His command of Jihad with obedience and appropriate speech ('we hear and we obey'). Then, when the command was determined, they proved by their deeds that they were true to the covenant they made with their Lord. If they had done so, it would have been better for them; but they chose the path of ruin for themselves.\n\n'Obedience' (Ta'atun) is in the nominative case as the subject, and the predicate (khabar) is omitted. We have been pointing to this style of Arabic—showing: when all attention is to be focused on the subject, the predicate is omitted. 'Appropriate speech' (qawlun ma'roof) refers to the statement: 'we hear and we obey.' Regarding the matters of Allah and His messenger, this statement has the position of the rule of the believers. His sincere and loyal servants have always welcomed His commands with this statement. This was suitable for them when they claimed to believe; but they, as soon as they heard of Jihad, were overcome by the agony of death.\n\n'And when the matter [of fighting] was determined'—meaning when the final decision of Jihad was made, and they prepared to take action.\n\nThe meaning is: what was suitable for them was to welcome the mention of Jihad with 'we hear and we obey', and then when the final decision was made, prove the truth of their word through their deeds. It should be kept in mind: the command given in verse 4 of this Surah was not of actual action, but of preparing for Jihad. The action came after it.\n\n'if they had been true to Allah, it would have been better for them'—meaning until now, whatever they said to the Prophet was a mere claim. The test of the truth of this claim came now. In this test, if they proved by their deeds that they were true, it would have opened the doors of great good for them; but they chose the path of cowardice."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 22,
        "Tafseer": "\"Would you perhaps, if you turned away, cause corruption on earth and sever your [ties of] relationship?\" (22)\n\nAdvice to the Hypocrites\n\nIn the preceding verses, the comment on the hypocrites was in the third-person style, but in this verse, they are addressed directly. This change of style is to make the advice more effective. It states: if you turn away from this invitation, you will not bring any benefit to yourselves or to your nation. You will only return to that corruption and bradar-kushi (killing of brothers) in which you were caught during the Jahiliyyah. The meaning is: if you desire this, you are free to choose whatever path you please and face its end; but if you desire true peace and justice in place of corruption, and want to see relationships established on the correct foundation of brotherhood, the sole path is to dedicate your life to establish this religion which is demolishing shirk and tribal biases of the Jahiliyyah to gather the progeny of Adam on His worship and the oneness of Adam.\n\nThe True Path of Peace and Reconciliation\n\nAddressing the hypocrites specifically to give this advice was required because among them was a group who desired a compromise with the disbelievers of the Quraysh. In Surah Al-Baqarah, such a group was mentioned, and below in verse 35 of this Surah, its mention is coming. These people assured the Quraysh and the Jews: 'Although we are included among the Muslims, in some matters we will support you.' Below in verse 26 of this Surah, this group will be mentioned. They succeeded in covering up their hypocrisy as long as the stage of war had not come; but when it came, no room remained for them to hide. They were not ready to draw their swords against the Quraysh; and to remain included among the Muslims, they began to whisper: 'We do not like bloodshed between brothers; rather, we want that the Muslims, the Quraysh, and other elements of this land live in peace and love. This is the path of reform.' Under this cover of peace and love, they presented their policy and influenced those within whom were the Jinn of hypocrisy. Pointing to this, He stated: 'This path you have chosen, and want others to choose, is not the path of peace, but is your return to that corruption and bradar-kushi in which you were caught before.' The path of peace and brotherhood is: all live as His servants and the Children of Adam, and adopt that system of life which is established on the oneness of God and the oneness of Adam, and to which the Qur'an invites; this cannot be achieved by maintaining that ignorant system of life in which every tribe has a different god and a different father. It should be clear: in Islam, the collective system is based on the oneness of God and the oneness of Adam. This has been discussed in Surah An-Nisa'."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 23,
        "Tafseer": "\"Those are the ones whom Allah has cursed, so He deafened them and blinded their vision.\" (23)\n\nThe Hearts of the Hypocrites Have Become Hardened\n\nIt states: these are the ones whom Allah has cursed, making them deaf to hearing the truth and blind of insight. Allah showed them His light, and the reality was made clear to them, but they continuously turn back to look at their darkness. For this disregard of theirs, Allah cursed them and stripped away His light from them, which resulted in their ears being deaf and their eyes blind."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 24,
        "Tafseer": "The Rust of Hearts is Removed by Reflecting on the Qur'an\n\n\"Then do they not reflect upon the Qur'an, or are there locks upon [their] hearts?\" (24)\n\nIt states: the thing which gives life to hearts is the Qur'an, provided they reflect upon it; but these ungrateful people never reflect upon it, which has resulted in the rust of bad deeds covering their hearts in such a way that they have been closed like locked doors.\n\nThe indefiniteness (tankeer) of 'quloob' (hearts) is to express aversion and disgust. Its parallel has passed in verse 47 of Surah An-Nisa', where addressing the People of the Book, He stated: 'Believe in what We have sent down, confirming what is with you, before We obliterate faces and turn them toward their backs'. Just as the indefiniteness of 'wujooh' (faces) there is to express disgust, similarly here, 'quloob' (hearts) is indefinite to express disgust. As if: these hearts are so disgusting and bad that the speaker does not even tolerate pointing to them with specification. 'Aqfalaha' (their locks) refers to those things which cover the heart like rust. The components of this rust have been mentioned in this Surah (for example, in verse 20 and below in verse 29) and are described in detail in other places in the Qur'an—the love of the world, fear of death, miserliness, cowardice, malice, envy, hypocrisy, etc. If power is received, pride and hardness are also added. The cure for these diseases is to hear and understand the Qur'an, as has been explained in verses 23-24 of Surah Al-Anfal; but such people feel the greatest aversion specifically to the Qur'an; because of this, their cure becomes impossible."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 25,
        "Tafseer": "\"Indeed, those who reverted back [to disbelief] after guidance had become clear to them - Satan enticed them and prolonged hope for them.\" (25)\n\nHypocrisy Is Reversion\n\nIt states: this approach of these hypocrites is of reversion (irtidad). The reality had become clear to them: the path of truth is what the Prophet is inviting to. Thus, they believed in it; but when trials were faced, Satan deceived them, and they fell into his deceptions, and God also granted them respite; because those who, in following their desires, turn away from the path of truth, Allah grants them respite to wander in whatever valley they please.\n\nHypocrisy's being reversion is clear from other places in the Qur'an. In verse 54 of Surah Al-Ma'idah, pointing to these hypocrites, He stated: 'O you who have believed, whoever of you should revert from his religion - Allah will bring forth [in place of them] a people He will love and who will love Him...' (An-Nisa': 136)—meaning: whoever among you wishes to revert from his religion, let him revert, God does not care. He will soon bring those whom He will love and who will love Him.\n\nThe subject of 'amla' (prolonged hope) here is Allah Almighty. In the Qur'an, this verb has occurred for Allah Almighty, and His being the subject is suitable. Attributing it to Satan is not suitable. If the context is present, the verb itself shows who the subject is. Parallels are present. Have a look at verse 110 of Surah Yusuf."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 26,
        "Tafseer": "\"That is because they said to those who disliked what Allah revealed, 'We will obey you in part of the matter.' And Allah knows their secrets.\" (26)\n\nThe Cause of the Hypocrites' Being Cast out\n\nThat is: Allah Almighty handed them over to Satan because even after the truth had become clear, they maintained their contact with those who disliked what Allah revealed. They assured them: 'In some matters we will continue supporting you.' 'those who disliked what Allah revealed' points to the Jews and the leaders of the Quraysh, whose enmity with Islam was clear; but these hypocrites assured them: 'Although we are included among the Muslims, it does not mean no connection remains between us and you. If any difficulty is faced by you, you will see that we will support you.' Regarding these hypocrites, it is described in Surah Al-Hashr: they go to the Jews to assure them: if you are turned out from here, we will also go out with you, and will never care about anyone's word regarding you: 'If you are expelled, we will surely go out with you, and we will not obey, in regard to you, anyone - ever' (Al-Hashr: 11).\n\n'And Allah knows their secrets' (wallahu ya'lamu israrahum)—'israr' (secrets) refers to this very contact which was pointed to, and this sentence is not merely to inform, but of warning. The meaning is: Allah Almighty is fully aware of these secrets of theirs, and their end will soon appear."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 27,
        "Tafseer": "\"Then how [will it be] when the angels take them in death, striking their faces and their backs?\" (27)\n\nThe State of the Hypocrites at the Time of Death\n\nThis describes their end—showing: those who make such conspiracies against Islam, their punishment begins when the angels come to take their souls; so let them reflect on what they will do when the severe angels take their souls, striking their faces and their backs, and no helper will save them."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 28,
        "Tafseer": "\"That is because they followed what angered Allah and disliked His pleasure, so He rendered worthless their deeds.\" (28)\n\nThat is, this dealing will be with them because all their efforts were in opposing Allah Almighty. They chose what angered Him, and disliked what pleased Him. As a retribution, the angels will begin to punish them at the time of death, and He will make all those deeds go to waste which they performed with their claim of faith."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 29,
        "Tafseer": "\"Or do those in whose hearts is disease think that Allah will never expose [their] rancor?\" (29)\n\nAllah Will Expose the Hypocrites\n\nThis is a threat to them—asking: do they assume that their slanders and conspiracies against Islam and Muslims will remain hidden, and Allah will never expose them? If so, this is incorrect. The time has arrived to lift the veil from their faces so that everyone recognizes them, and they can deceive no one.\n\n'Disease' (maradh) refers to hypocrisy and also to that malice and envy which they harbored against Islam and Muslims, and because of which they committed those actions mentioned above. Hypocrisy is in itself a disease, but it becomes severe when envy and malice are added. 'Adhghan' (rancor) points to this envy and malice. 'Adhghan' is the plural of 'dhighn', which means malice."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 30,
        "Tafseer": "\"And if We willed, We could show them to you, and you would know them by their mark; but you will surely know them by the tone of [their] speech. And Allah knows your deeds.\" (30)\n\n'Lahn' (tone) also means to use an encompassed style in speaking—meaning: a person speaks in such a way that he intends one meaning in his heart, but tries to show another to others. The hypocrites were expert in this. They spoke in such a double-tongued style that they wanted to convince both the disbelievers and the Muslims that their sympathies were with them.\n\nThis addresses the Prophet (pbuh) to threaten the hypocrites—stating: it is not in the least difficult for Allah to expose them in such a way that you recognize every one of them by his mark. If He is not doing so, it is His veiling; however, identifying them is not difficult for you. You can easily identify them by the double-tongued style of their speech, the dual nature of their words, and the hesitation of their tone.\n\n'And Allah knows your deeds' addresses the hypocrites directly—stating: if you succeed in deceiving the Muslims with your double-tongued speech, this success is no good thing for you. Allah Almighty is fully aware of your deeds, and since He is aware, what benefit will you achieve by hiding them from others!"
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 31,
        "Tafseer": "A Test to Distinguish the Pure and the Corrupt\n\n\"And We will surely test you until We make evident those who strive among you [for the cause of Allah] and the patient, and We will test your affairs.\" (31)\n\nThat is, through various favorable and unfavorable conditions, Allah Almighty will necessarily test you, until He clearly identifies who among you are those who perform Jihad in the path of Allah and remain steadfast, and who are mere champions of words. The meaning is: Allah's way is not to write on every hypocrite's forehead: 'he is a hypocrite'; but His Sunnah is inevitable: He tests to distinguish between the pure and the corrupt, and since this is His Sunnah, you must necessarily pass through this test, and those who want to remain among the Muslims through deception will not succeed in hiding themselves for long. If you reflect, this also showed: the primary objective of these tests is indeed to identify the mujahideen and the patient, but as a logical consequence, the states of those will also be exposed who want to enter this group through deception. 'and We will test your affairs' (wa nabluwa akhbarakum) points to this. 'Akhbar' refers to their states. In other words, understand: Allah Almighty tests people so that the butter of goodness stands manifest. But the result is that the whey of evil also stands manifest.\n\nSince this test is a requirement of the Sunnah of Allah, it is stated with the emphatic 'lam' (la-nabluwannakum). And 'knowing' (na'lama) here is in the sense of testing and distinguishing. Its explanation has passed."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 32,
        "Tafseer": "\"Indeed, those who disbelieve and avert [people] from the way of Allah and oppose the Messenger after guidance has become clear to them - never will they harm Allah at all, and He will render worthless their deeds.\" (32)\n\nWarning to the Hypocrites\n\nAt the end of the Surah, He repeated that theme with which the Surah began, and the objective, as will follow, is to warn the hypocrites: those who are opposing Allah and His messenger cannot harm Allah Almighty; they will only face defeat. All their efforts will go to waste in both this world and the Hereafter. So do not follow them to ruin your world and your Hereafter, but obey Allah and His messenger with complete devotion; if you do not show weakness, Allah will grant you victory, and these opponents will be disgraced.\n\n'Indeed, those who disbelieve and avert [people] from the way of Allah' are words which indicate that the Quraysh and their allies are meant. In verse 1, they were mentioned with these words. 'and oppose the Messenger after guidance has become clear to them' is their further attribute—showing: it has become clear to them that the religion of Allah to which His messenger invites is indeed the truth, but they are bent upon opposing him purely in the pride of their leadership. Their opposition cannot harm the religion of Allah, but they will destroy themselves. The meaning is: when they have stood to oppose His messenger while knowing him to be His messenger and his invitation to be the truth, how long will this artificial strength of theirs support them? Ultimately they will surrender and be disgraced."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 33,
        "Tafseer": "\"O you who have believed, obey Allah and obey the Messenger and do not invalidate your deeds.\" (33)\n\nObey Allah Rising Above Your Personal Interests\n\nThe address is general, but the context indicates that the. target are those weak Muslims who have been mentioned—stating: 'O you who have believed, the requirement of this faith of yours is that you obey Allah and His messenger.' The context indicates that 'obey' (ati'oo) is in its perfect and true meaning—implying: obey every command of Allah and His messenger in all conditions, rising above your personal interests and welfare.\n\n'and do not invalidate your deeds'—meaning only through this kind of obedience will your deeds be fruitful; if you make this obedience subordinate to your personal interests, remember that all your deeds will go to waste, even if they are deeds of religion. Allah accept only that faith which is in accordance with His conditions; those who want to believe on their own conditions and obey Him only to the extent of their interests, their religion is thrown in their faces; so do not commit any such thing to waste your deeds."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 34,
        "Tafseer": "\"Indeed, those who disbelieve and avert [people] from the way of Allah and then die while they are disbelievers - never will Allah forgive them.\" (34)\n\nThat is: Allah Almighty is never going to forgive those who chose the path of disbelief, turned others away from His path, and died while they were disbelievers. The meaning is: the same end will be faced by those who take their support and make conspiracies to maintain friendship with them."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 35,
        "Tafseer": "\"So do not weaken and call for peace while you are superior; and Allah is with you and will never deprive you of [the reward of] your deeds.\" (35)\n\nA Plan of the Hypocrites to Cover Up Their Cowardice\n\n'Silm' means peace and compromise. Under verses 22-23 above, we mentioned: since the hypocrites did not possess the courage for war, they talked of peace and compromise. They advised the Muslims as well: 'We should try to resolve matters through peace instead of war,' and presented themselves as a peace-loving party, giving people the impression: in adopting this policy lies the welfare of this country, otherwise there will be bloodshed between brothers, and the entire structure of the nation will collapse. This policy of theirs was based on their cowardice and self-interest, but they presented it in the guise of peace and love, and influenced those within whom were the Jinn of hypocrisy. In this verse, their weakness is exposed—showing: do not weaken to invite to peace, but stand up for Jihad with resolve and faith. If you stand up with true faith, you will be superior, and your enemies will be disgraced. Allah is with you, and when He is with you, His help will be with you at every step, and remain assured: Allah will never show any unfaithfulness or disregard regarding the reward of your deeds, but will give you a full reward for your every deed.\n\nA Point of the Language\n\nIn 'So do not weaken and call for peace' (fala tahinoo wa tad'oo ilas-silm), the same style is observed as has been discussed under verse 42 of Surah Al-Baqarah: 'And do not mix the truth with falsehood or conceal the truth'. Where the same reality is expressed in both the conjoined and the conjoining clauses, there is no need to repeat the negative 'la'. Such is the case here. Since their invitation to peace was the result of their cowardice, 'tad'oo' was conjoined with 'fala tahinoo' and 'la' was omitted so that from the style itself, it is clarified: 'You are not inviting to peace because you are peace-loving, but this is a failed attempt to cover up your cowardice.'\n\n'Watr' means to diminish or show unfaithfulness. 'lan yatirakum amalahum' means: 'Do not have this fear of Allah that He will show any unfaithfulness or disregard regarding your deeds, but He will give you a full reward.' When every deed is to receive a full reward, there is no reason to hesitate in making sacrifices in His path."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 36,
        "Tafseer": "\"Indeed, the life of this world is only amusement and diversion. And if you believe and fear Allah, He will give you your rewards and not ask of you your properties.\" (36)\n\nEncouraging Those of Weak Resolve\n\nThat is, do not hesitate in sacrificing your life and wealth in His path in being entangled in the love of this world. The value of this world's wealth is only if some earning is cultivated for the Hereafter; if someone has not cultivated for the Hereafter, he has spent his life in vain. Remain assured: if you adopt a life of faith and piety and spend your wealth in His path, this is no losing bargain; rather, Allah Almighty will give you a full reward for your every deed, and you will achieve the eternal kingdom in exchange for the broken pieces of clay of this world.\n\nAfter 'and not ask of you your properties' (wa la yas'alkum amwalakum), the word 'ihfa'an' (persistently) is omitted. Its explanation is coming in the subsequent verse; because of this, He omitted it here. Explaining after a brief mention is well-known in the Qur'an. This is also why questions are quoted briefly, because the reply clarifies them. We have explained this under 'They ask you concerning the new moons' (Al-Baqarah: 189). The meaning is: remain assured that Allah Almighty will never place you in this test of demanding your entire property; rather, He will ask only a part of it, and will fully reward you for it, so there is no cause of fear or anxiety regarding spending in His path."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 37,
        "Tafseer": "\"If He should ask you for them and press you, you would withhold, and He would expose your rancor.\" (37)\n\nAllah Almighty is Highly Generous in Testing His Servants\n\nThat is, Allah Almighty will not demand your entire property because if He did so, your entire secret would be exposed—showing that you would withhold, and in this way, that envy and malice which you harbor in your chests against Islam and Muslims would stand manifest. In verse 29 above, a threat was given to the hypocrites: they should not remain in the delusion that Allah will cover up their envy and malice; He can expose them whenever He pleases by placing them in some trial. This same point is stated here from another aspect—showing: Allah Almighty could demand that you hand over your entire property, because this property is His gift; but He does not do so because such a test would expose those whose miserliness and hypocrisy are covered. The meaning is: remain grateful for His generosity that He has not placed you in any such test, otherwise He could expose your secret."
    },
    {
        "SurahNumber": 47,
        "AyahNumber": 38,
        "Tafseer": "\"Here you are - those invited to spend in the cause of Allah - but among you are those who withhold. And whoever withholds only withholds from himself. And Allah is the Free of need, while you are the needy. And if you turn away, He will replace you with another people; then they will not be the likes of you.\" (38)\n\nThreat to the Miserly\n\n'Ha-antum ha'ula'i' (Here you are) is an expression of regret and sorrow over the state of the hypocrites—showing: 'You are being invited to spend in His path, yet you are showing miserliness as if you are giving to someone else, whereas showing miserliness to God is showing miserliness to yourselves. Allah asks of you not for Himself, but for you—so that He may reward you with the eternal kingdom. Allah is entirely self-sufficient, and you are the needy; He is not needy.'\n\n'And if you turn away, He will replace you with another people; then they will not be the likes of you'—this is a threat to the hypocrites: 'Your approach is of reversion. If you wish to choose reversion, do so. Allah has no need of you. He will soon raise others for the service of His religion who will not be weak and useless like you.' In Surah Al-Ma'idah, this was stated addressing the hypocrites: 'O you who have believed, whoever of you should revert from his religion - Allah will bring forth [in place of them] a people He will love and who will love Him [who are] humble toward the believers, powerful against the disbelievers' (54).\n\nIn the light of the verse of Surah Al-Ma'idah, explain 'then they will not be the likes of you' (thumma la yakoonoo amthalakum)—showing: 'You harbor malice against Allah and are averse to His pleasure, so He is also displeased with you. On the contrary, they will love Allah and seek His pleasure; therefore, Allah will also love them. Your state is: you are very soft for the disbelievers, seeking their friendship, and they are using you as they please against Islam and Muslims. On the contrary, they will indeed be highly kind and compassionate toward the believers, but if the disbelievers try to use them for their purposes, they will find them like a rock.'\n\nBy the favor and guidance of Allah, the commentary of this Surah is completed on these lines. Praise be to Allah, Lord of the worlds.\n\nRahman Abad\n9 September, 1976 AD\n13 Ramadan, 1396 AH."
